<p>The <b>Black Speech</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Constructed_language" title="Constructed language">constructed language</a> devised by J. R. R. Tolkien.</p>
<p>One of the <a href="/wiki/Languages_of_Arda" title="Languages of Arda" class="mw-redirect">languages of Arda</a> in Tolkien's <a href="/wiki/Middle-earth" title="Middle-earth">Middle-earth</a> <a href="/wiki/Tolkien%27s_legendarium" title="Tolkien's legendarium">legendarium</a>, it was spoken in the <a href="/wiki/Realm" title="Realm">realm</a> of <a href="/wiki/Mordor" title="Mordor">Mordor</a>. Tolkien describes the language as being created by <a href="/wiki/Sauron" title="Sauron">Sauron</a> as an <a href="/wiki/Artificial_language" title="Artificial language" class="mw-redirect">artificial language</a> to be the sole language of all the servants of Mordor, thereby replacing the many different varieties of <a href="/wiki/Orc_(Middle-earth)" title="Orc (Middle-earth)">Orkish</a> and other languages used by his servants. Tolkien describes the language as existing in two forms, the ancient "pure" forms used by Sauron himself, the <a href="/wiki/Nazg%C3%BBl" title="Nazgûl">Nazgûl</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/Olog-hai" title="Olog-hai" class="mw-redirect">Olog-hai</a>, and the more "debased" form used by the soldiery of the <a href="/wiki/Barad-d%C3%BBr" title="Barad-dûr">Barad-dûr</a> at the end of the <a href="/wiki/Third_Age" title="Third Age">Third Age</a>.</p>
